AGI - "I don't know the specific case, but I can assume that the attack was triggered by possessivity. Many owners interpret the dog's affection as an emotional dependence, without understanding that often the dog considers them a resource to defend." Ivan Raimo, a certified trainer Ente Nazionale della Cinofilia Italiana, an expert in behavioral rehabilitation in Campania, analyzes what happened in Acerra, where a pitbull unbraded a nine-month-old girl.
&nbsp;
According to the trainer, the aggressiveness of the dog is not related to the breed, but to the management and genetic selection. "The pitbull, in its original selection, was not aggressive to man. The problem arises from uncontrolled couplings that produce unstable specimens, without anyone verifying the character", he explains.
&nbsp;
Raimo has faced several cases of dogs with behavioral problems: "I followed a pitbull that for two and a half years had never left the house. When we finally brought him out, he attacked everything for fear. After four months of rehabilitation, he walks peacefully." Another case concerned a dog with strong aggressiveness both towards man and other dogs. "We educated him by channeling his energy on an object: today, instead of attacking, discharges tension on a brine," he adds.
&nbsp;
"A license for the owners - he observes - could be useful, but only if structured well. In Milan they experienced a license without even the presence of dogs. If training is not practical, it is useless." Raimo is said to be skeptical on an obligation that does not foresee a true educational path for the owners.
&nbsp;
"In Germany and Switzerland there are compulsory training courses for those who adopt a demanding dog. In Italy, however, anyone can buy a pitbull without the slightest preparation, and the consequences are under the eyes of all," he says. The key to preventing similar episodes is a controlled genetic selection mix and greater responsibility by the owners. "Without clear rules on management and breeding, tragedies such as Acerra will continue to repeat," concludes the trainer.&nbsp;
